Job Description:
•	Conduct desk research on migrants’ rights and needs in Tajikistan with a special focus on women affected by migration; 
•	Follow the ongoing events, news, and policy and legislation updates related to migrants’ rights and needs in Tajikistan;
•	Analyze relevant legislations and policies;
•	Collect primary and secondary data using applicable data collection methods;
•	Identify the target group among migrants, relevant civil society organizations (CSO), and state authorities; 
•	Develop a methodology with a number of interviews required among three target groups; 
•	Prepare questionnaires for the target groups;  
•	Conduct surveys among three target groups: migrants, CSOs and state agencies (in person or virtually);
•	Conduct data analysis based on both primary and secondary data;
•	Identify issues related to migrants’ rights and needs in general and gender-based discrimination with regard to access to health care, social services, and decent work conditions in particular; 
•	Elaborate recommendations for state authorities on developing evidence-based policy taking into account migration, human rights, and gender equality considerations;
•	Prepare a monitoring report with recommendations;
•	Present results to relevant stakeholders.

Job description:
• Develop methodology and tools for the research;
• Update criteria for selecting the most favorable countries for labor migration from Kyrgyzstan based on the best practices and international standards enshrined in UN and ILO international treaties;
• Analyze and assess the most favorable countries for the employment of Kyrgyz migrant workers;
• Based on the developed criteria, review the labor migration situation in countries of Europe (Belgium, Germany, Spain, France, Italy, Turkey, United Kingdom), Asia (Japan, Republic of Korea), North America (the US, Canada) and Middle East (UAE).
• Develop recommendations for government agencies, NGOs, and the private sector in Kyrgyzstan to diversify labor migration and its effective management.

 Deliverables: 
• Developed profile of 12 countries of  potential destination  for migrant workers with the review of domestic  laws and policies on labor migration, bilateral and regional agreements, national labor law requirements, migrants’ access to social and health systems, protection from exploitation and access to consular protection and diaspora engagement. 
• A report with recommendations for Kyrgyz government agencies, NGOs, and the private sector to facilitate the legitimate employment of Kyrgyz migrants in the selected countries was prepared (currently under the revision).
